1
00:00:56,456 --> 00:00:57,683
Come on!

2
00:02:21,106 --> 00:02:23,836
But you realize
I know nothing about politics?

3
00:02:23,977 --> 00:02:26,377
- You voted for him, didn't you?
- Adam Lang? Of course I did.

4
00:02:26,445 --> 00:02:29,745
Everyone voted for him.
He wasn't a politician, he was a craze.

5
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:31,146
Well, there you go.

6
00:02:31,216 --> 00:02:35,778
Look, it's a new ghostwriter he needs,
not another goddamn politico.

7
00:02:36,156 --> 00:02:38,989
He was paid $10 million for these memoirs,

8
00:02:39,057 --> 00:02:42,026
but rumor has it
the manuscript's a crock of shit.

9
00:02:42,094 --> 00:02:45,258
Rhinehart's lending him his house
at the ocean so they can fix it,

10
00:02:45,430 --> 00:02:48,058
and the pressure
must have gotten to McAra.

11
00:02:48,401 --> 00:02:50,800
Pathologist said his blood was,
like, three parts booze.

12
00:02:50,870 --> 00:02:52,929
You mean he drowned by accident?

13
00:02:53,173 --> 00:02:56,574
Accident, suicide, who cares?
It was the book that killed him.

14
00:02:56,808 --> 00:02:57,901
Well, that's encouraging.

15
00:02:59,145 --> 00:03:00,840
Who is this McAra?
Should I have heard of him?

16
00:03:00,913 --> 00:03:04,907
Yeah. He was some kind of aide to Lang
when he was Prime Minister,

17
00:03:04,984 --> 00:03:07,850
so don't admit that you haven't.
He was with him for years.

18
00:03:10,856 --> 00:03:12,586
I don't know, Rick.

19
00:03:15,495 --> 00:03:18,157
This is a great opportunity for you.

20
00:03:18,330 --> 00:03:20,299
Plus the money is good. Kids won't starve.

21
00:03:20,365 --> 00:03:22,265
- I don't have any kids.
- I do.

22
00:03:36,848 --> 00:03:37,941
Roy.

23
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:43,817
Who're you expecting to bomb you,
Random House?

24
00:03:43,889 --> 00:03:45,288
We're publishing Lang's memoirs.

25
00:03:45,358 --> 00:03:47,985
That's enough to make us a target,
apparently.

26
00:03:48,594 --> 00:03:49,960
Thank you.

27
00:03:59,239 --> 00:04:03,073
- How many have you seen?
- Five. You're the last.

28
00:04:10,682 --> 00:04:11,911
I must be honest.

29
00:04:11,985 --> 00:04:14,146
I don't think you're the right man
for this assignment.

30
00:04:14,219 --> 00:04:15,983
Then it's a good job
it's not your decision, Roy.

31
00:04:18,591 --> 00:04:21,685
John Maddox, chief executive
of Rhinehart, New York.

32
00:04:21,761 --> 00:04:22,750
Sir.

33
00:04:24,062 --> 00:04:26,553
Sidney Kroll,
Mr. Lang's Washington attorney.

34
00:04:26,632 --> 00:04:27,622
Mr. Kroll.

35
00:04:27,699 --> 00:04:30,692
And Nick Ricardelli I believe you know.

36
00:04:31,069 --> 00:04:32,058
All right, Rick.

37
00:04:36,042 --> 00:04:39,273
All right, I gather from Rick
you're aware of the situation?

38
00:04:40,713 --> 00:04:42,112
Perhaps you can enlighten us

39
00:04:42,180 --> 00:04:45,308
and tell us what exactly
you're gonna bring to this project.

40
00:04:45,418 --> 00:04:46,646
Nothing.

41
00:04:49,088 --> 00:04:51,283
No, I'm not gonna pretend
to be someone I'm not.

42
00:04:51,356 --> 00:04:52,846
You have my CV.

43
00:04:52,925 --> 00:04:56,223
His last effort was
the autobiography of a magician,

44
00:04:56,295 --> 00:04:58,560
<i>I Came, I Sawed, I Conquered.</i>

45
00:04:58,630 --> 00:05:01,360
Yeah, and it went straight
to number one, so...

46
00:05:01,434 --> 00:05:03,595
After you turned it down, Roy.

47
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:08,233
Look, I don't read political memoirs.
Who does?

48
00:05:09,475 --> 00:05:13,069
And I gather you've spent
$10 million on this book.

49
00:05:13,478 --> 00:05:15,709
How much of that are you gonna see back?

50
00:05:15,781 --> 00:05:17,908
Two? Three?

51
00:05:17,983 --> 00:05:20,247
It's bad news for your shareholders.

52
00:05:20,319 --> 00:05:23,312
And it's worse news
for your client, Mr. Kroll.

53
00:05:23,389 --> 00:05:28,088
Adam Lang, he wants a place in history,
not in the remainder tables.

54
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:29,252
Oh, please!

55
00:05:29,329 --> 00:05:31,524
It's because I know nothing about politics

56
00:05:31,596 --> 00:05:35,293
that I'll ask the questions that get
right to the heart of who Adam Lang is.

57
00:05:35,468 --> 00:05:37,834
And that is what sells autobiographies.

58
00:05:38,437 --> 00:05:39,632
Heart.

59
00:05:41,540 --> 00:05:43,975
Wow! That's nicely done.

60
00:05:44,043 --> 00:05:46,670
- What utter balls.
- You think so?

61
00:05:46,745 --> 00:05:50,442
John, of course.
Adam Lang's a world historical figure.

62
00:05:50,516 --> 00:05:52,983
His autobiography is gonna be
a world-publishing event.

63
00:05:53,052 --> 00:05:55,781
Yeah, well, I got warehouses filled with

64
00:05:55,855 --> 00:05:58,516
world-publishing events
waiting to be pulped.

65
00:06:00,093 --> 00:06:01,185
Sid?

66
00:06:01,961 --> 00:06:05,862
Adam is obviously still very upset
by what happened to Mike McAra.

67
00:06:05,932 --> 00:06:10,300
He was irreplaceable.
Irreplaceable, and yet he has to be replaced.

68
00:06:11,370 --> 00:06:15,865
Adam can certainly appreciate the benefits
of trying someone different.

69
00:06:15,942 --> 00:06:19,139
In the end, it's about chemistry.
Do you work out, maybe?

70
00:06:19,211 --> 00:06:21,646
- Not really.
- That's a pity. Adam likes to work out.

71
00:06:21,713 --> 00:06:25,206
Actually, I know a good writer
on the <i>Guardian</i> who uses a gym.

72
00:06:26,985 --> 00:06:31,548
Okay, maybe we could just run over
the publishing schedule, yeah?

73
00:06:31,624 --> 00:06:33,057
We need to wrap this up in a month.

74
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:34,353
- A month?
- Yes.

75
00:06:34,427 --> 00:06:36,588
- You want the book in a month?
- We already have a first draft.

76
00:06:36,661 --> 00:06:39,290
Yeah, well, it needs a lot of work.

77
00:06:39,899 --> 00:06:44,233
That's why I like your résumé here.
You're fast, and you deliver.

78
00:06:44,302 --> 00:06:47,100
You name it, he ghosts it.

79
00:06:47,340 --> 00:06:48,704
And you're a Brit.

80
00:06:49,675 --> 00:06:50,869
The ghost should be a Brit.

81
00:06:50,942 --> 00:06:53,069
To get the jolly old tone right, right?

82
00:06:54,579 --> 00:06:58,538
- Do you have any family commitments?
- No, I have no family. Why?

83
00:06:58,617 --> 00:07:00,346
Adam is locked into a US lecture tour,

84
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:04,480
also a fundraising program
for the Adam Lang Foundation.

85
00:07:04,557 --> 00:07:06,649
It's a month in the States. That's okay.

86
00:07:06,725 --> 00:07:08,694
Couldn't I bring the manuscript back here
to work on?

87
00:07:08,761 --> 00:07:13,129
I'm afraid not. It's in a secure environment
in Marty Rhinehart's own house.

88
00:07:13,399 --> 00:07:15,560
Only a few people are allowed to handle it.

89
00:07:15,634 --> 00:07:17,192
Sounds more like a bomb than a book.

90
00:07:19,204 --> 00:07:23,471
I will need to see it myself at some point.
I am supposed to be editing it.

91
00:07:23,543 --> 00:07:26,978
Yeah, in theory.
Actually, we need to talk about that.

92
00:07:29,014 --> 00:07:30,846
- How soon can you get over there?
- As soon as you want.

93
00:07:30,917 --> 00:07:32,043
- He'll fly tonight.
- Rick.

94
00:07:32,117 --> 00:07:33,106
It's okay.

95
00:07:41,093 --> 00:07:42,526
Okay, you're in.

96
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:44,918
Oh!

97
00:07:45,031 --> 00:07:47,055
- Congratulations.
- Thank you. Thanks.

98
00:07:47,132 --> 00:07:48,531
- Rick.
- Thank you.

99
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:51,262
Actually, I have something here

100
00:07:51,336 --> 00:07:52,531
- you might want to look at.
- Is that... Is that...

101
00:07:52,605 --> 00:07:55,403
No, no, no, this isn't Adam's book.
No, it's another client of mine.

102
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:57,908
Yeah, perhaps you can let me know
what you think.

103
00:07:59,278 --> 00:08:00,370
Sure.

104
00:08:00,446 --> 00:08:02,242
Okay, if you're gonna get
that evening flight,

105
00:08:02,314 --> 00:08:04,749
we'd better talk contracts with Rick here.

106
00:08:04,817 --> 00:08:07,615
Wanna show our friend to the door?
Would you?

107
00:08:07,786 --> 00:08:08,879
Roy?

108
00:08:10,889 --> 00:08:12,824
Call you in an hour, buddy.

109
00:08:12,992 --> 00:08:13,980
Hey!

110
00:08:14,459 --> 00:08:15,518
Remember...

111
00:08:17,663 --> 00:08:19,153
Heart.

112
00:08:22,401 --> 00:08:25,961
There's something not quite right
about this project.

113
00:08:26,137 --> 00:08:28,129
- What? Me, you mean?
- Obviously you.

114
00:08:28,307 --> 00:08:30,639
And McAra. Suicide?

115
00:08:31,810 --> 00:08:34,745
He didn't strike me as the suicidal type.

116
00:08:34,913 --> 00:08:36,643
Always nice to see you, Roy.

117
00:08:39,418 --> 00:08:40,645
Good luck.

118
00:08:53,231 --> 00:08:55,529
Oh, God.

119
00:09:10,883 --> 00:09:12,373
Thank you.

120
00:09:53,893 --> 00:09:55,918
- Yeah?
- <i>Congratulations!</i>

121
00:09:55,995 --> 00:09:58,554
- On what?
<i>- On having me as your agent.</i>

122
00:09:58,730 --> 00:10:00,721
Yeah, I can hardly believe my luck.

123
00:10:00,899 --> 00:10:01,889
<i>Are you packed?</i>

124
00:10:01,967 --> 00:10:03,400
I just got mugged.

125
00:10:04,604 --> 00:10:07,333
<i>Shit! Are you okay?</i>

126
00:10:07,405 --> 00:10:11,240
Yeah, all they took was the manuscript
that Sidney Kroll gave me.

127
00:10:11,409 --> 00:10:12,933
<i>What? Why?</i>

128
00:10:13,278 --> 00:10:15,008
I don't know. You tell me.

129
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:16,904
<i>Are you hurt?</i>

130
00:10:16,982 --> 00:10:20,076
No, I'm fine. I think they must
have followed me from Rhinehart's.

131
00:10:21,187 --> 00:10:22,950
<i>Why would they do that?</i>

132
00:10:23,121 --> 00:10:26,023
Well, maybe they thought
I had Lang's book.

133
00:10:26,192 --> 00:10:28,456
I knew this whole thing was a bad idea.

134
00:10:30,229 --> 00:10:31,719
<i>You're still okay to fly tonight, right?</i>

135
00:10:31,797 --> 00:10:33,889
For God's sake, Rick, I'm in shock.

136
00:10:33,966 --> 00:10:36,298
<i>Well, here's another shock for you.</i>

137
00:10:36,469 --> 00:10:39,267
<i>For one month's work</i>
<i>on a manuscript that's already written,</i>

138
00:10:39,337 --> 00:10:45,277
<i>Rhinehart Inc. Is willing</i>
<i>to pay you $250,000, plus expenses.</i>

139
00:10:46,611 --> 00:10:48,307
<i>Window seat or aisle?</i>

140
00:10:48,713 --> 00:10:51,945
<i>...Islam has</i>
<i>issued a statement claiming responsibility.</i>

141
00:10:52,018 --> 00:10:54,952
<i>We hope to bring you more on that</i>
<i>later in the bulletin.</i>

142
00:10:55,020 --> 00:10:59,048
<i>Meanwhile, former British Prime Minister</i>
<i>Adam Lang is back in the news tonight.</i>

143
00:10:59,158 --> 00:11:01,990
<i>According to leaked documents,</i>
<i>Mr. Lang authorized</i>

144
00:11:02,061 --> 00:11:04,221
<i>the illegal use of British special forces</i>

145
00:11:04,296 --> 00:11:08,322
<i>to seize four suspected al-Qaeda terrorists</i>
<i>in Pakistan</i>

146
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:12,167
<i>and then hand them over</i>
<i>for interrogation by the CIA.</i>

147
00:11:12,337 --> 00:11:16,467
<i>The men, Nasir Ashraf, Marwat Sayed,</i>
<i>Salim Khan and Faruk Ahmed,</i>

148
00:11:16,542 --> 00:11:21,479
<i>all British citizens, were seized in the</i>
<i>Pakistani city of Peshawar five years ago.</i>

149
00:11:21,880 --> 00:11:25,009
<i>All four were allegedly transferred</i>
<i>out of the country</i>

150
00:11:25,083 --> 00:11:27,518
<i>to a secret location and tortured.</i>

151
00:11:27,586 --> 00:11:29,918
<i>Mr. Ashraf is reported to have died</i>
<i>under interrogation.</i>

152
00:11:31,090 --> 00:11:33,081
<i>Such an operation</i>
<i>would have been illegal under...</i>

153
00:11:33,158 --> 00:11:34,786
- <i>Yeah?</i>
- Where are you?

154
00:11:34,860 --> 00:11:38,226
<i>Heathrow, like you.</i>
<i>Waiting for my flight to New York.</i>

155
00:11:38,297 --> 00:11:39,286
Can you see the news?

156
00:11:39,365 --> 00:11:41,889
<i>The Lang story? Yeah, I'm watching it now.</i>

157
00:11:41,966 --> 00:11:44,230
What have you gotten me into?

158
00:11:44,302 --> 00:11:48,763
<i>I got you into a quarter of a million bucks,</i>
<i>pal, that's what I got you into.</i>

159
00:11:49,008 --> 00:11:50,407
<i>They're calling my flight. I gotta go.</i>

160
00:11:50,475 --> 00:11:51,942
Listen, I just realized

161
00:11:52,010 --> 00:11:54,774
Sidney Kroll could have given me
that manuscript deliberately

162
00:11:54,846 --> 00:11:57,713
so it would look like
I was carrying Lang's book.

163
00:11:57,783 --> 00:11:59,044
<i>Why the hell would he do that?</i>

164
00:11:59,118 --> 00:12:02,849
I don't know. To use me as a tethered goat?

165
00:12:04,123 --> 00:12:06,852
<i>Get some sleep on the plane.</i>
<i>You're sounding weird.</i>

166
00:12:06,926 --> 00:12:10,384
<i>"A tethered goat."</i>
<i>I'll call you next week.</i>

167
00:12:10,462 --> 00:12:12,590
<i>...and long-term psychological trauma.</i>

168
00:12:12,664 --> 00:12:14,131
<i>In other words, torture.</i>

169
00:12:14,667 --> 00:12:15,860
Hello, sir.
Would you like a newspaper to read?

170
00:12:15,934 --> 00:12:18,198
- Have you got the <i>Evening Standard?</i>
- We do, yes.

171
00:12:18,269 --> 00:12:19,897
Thanks. Thank you.

172
00:12:20,172 --> 00:12:21,900
Hello, madam.
Would you like a newspaper to read?

173
00:12:21,974 --> 00:12:24,738
Yes, please. Thank you.

174
00:13:52,063 --> 00:13:53,258
Passport?

175
00:14:59,230 --> 00:15:01,255
This is an absolute scandal!

176
00:15:01,332 --> 00:15:02,322
Amelia Bly. Welcome.

177
00:15:03,469 --> 00:15:04,561
I'm Adam's assistant.

178
00:15:04,636 --> 00:15:08,333
Adam's in New York, unfortunately,
and won't be back until later this afternoon.

179
00:15:08,407 --> 00:15:11,068
Actually, forget I said that,
it's bloody ridiculous!

180
00:15:12,244 --> 00:15:15,475
Oh, dear. I'm so sorry.
I'm afraid Ruth's having one of those days.

181
00:15:15,547 --> 00:15:17,105
If this isn't a good time, I could go to...

182
00:15:17,182 --> 00:15:19,376
No, no. She's keen to meet you.

183
00:15:20,184 --> 00:15:23,052
- Right. Shall we make a start?
- Right.

184
00:15:24,889 --> 00:15:27,221
- How was your journey?
- Long.

185
00:15:27,393 --> 00:15:28,951
- We're a small team.
- Thanks.

186
00:15:29,028 --> 00:15:30,393
This is Alice.

187
00:15:30,763 --> 00:15:33,061
Lucy's traveling with Adam.

188
00:15:33,231 --> 00:15:36,793
We need another pair of hands, but Adam
couldn't bring himself to replace Mike.

189
00:15:36,869 --> 00:15:38,961
- They were together so long.
- How long were you with him?

190
00:15:39,038 --> 00:15:41,437
Eight years.
I'm an attachment from Number 10.

191
00:15:41,539 --> 00:15:43,131
Ah. Poor Number 10.

192
00:15:43,207 --> 00:15:44,640
Before I show you the manuscript,

193
00:15:44,710 --> 00:15:47,701
I need you to sign
this confidentiality agreement.

194
00:15:52,250 --> 00:15:53,513
Sign here.

195
00:15:57,355 --> 00:15:58,618
And here.

196
00:16:00,426 --> 00:16:01,756
And here.

197
00:16:12,705 --> 00:16:14,865
Wow, quite a place.

198
00:16:15,407 --> 00:16:17,033
Don't you get Ionely at night?

199
00:16:17,176 --> 00:16:18,802
It's my husband I miss the most.

200
00:16:18,876 --> 00:16:21,038
Are you married?
I noticed you don't wear a wedding ring.

201
00:16:21,113 --> 00:16:23,138
I can't, sadly. It's far too large.

202
00:16:23,215 --> 00:16:26,378
- It bleeps when I go through airport security.
- Oh.

203
00:16:27,586 --> 00:16:28,985
Here we are.

204
00:16:32,224 --> 00:16:36,388
The manuscript is not to be removed
from this room. It's not to be copied.

205
00:16:37,962 --> 00:16:40,898
You have six hours
before Adam gets in from New York.

206
00:16:40,966 --> 00:16:43,866
- Can you finish by then?
- I'll try.

207
00:16:44,570 --> 00:16:46,902
I'll ask Dep to bring you up
a sandwich for lunch.

208
00:16:46,971 --> 00:16:47,995
Thanks.

209
00:16:53,578 --> 00:16:54,705
Have fun.

210
00:17:02,254 --> 00:17:05,586
"Langs are Scottish folk,
originally, and proud of it.

211
00:17:05,656 --> 00:17:10,094
"Our name is a derivation of 'long,<i>'</i>
the Old English word for 'tall,<i>'</i>

212
00:17:10,162 --> 00:17:13,597
"and it is from north of the border
that my forefathers hail."

213
00:17:14,298 --> 00:17:15,288
Fuck.

214
00:17:17,102 --> 00:17:19,400
"My great-grandfather, Ebenezer Lang,

215
00:17:19,471 --> 00:17:23,237
"was born in 1862 in Pitlochry, Scotland.

216
00:17:23,307 --> 00:17:25,276
"One of nine children, seven of them boys."

217
00:17:25,344 --> 00:17:28,107
"The American President
was much taller than I had expected."

218
00:17:29,414 --> 00:17:32,406
"This year's European summit
was particularly interesting."

219
00:17:32,483 --> 00:17:35,384
"I always found the Queen, in private,
to have a delightful sense of humor."

220
00:17:54,405 --> 00:17:55,599
Thanks.

221
00:18:19,431 --> 00:18:23,491
"I've always been an optimist.
The present is where we live.

222
00:18:23,568 --> 00:18:27,436
"Ruth and I look forward to the future,
whatever it may hold."

223
00:18:31,276 --> 00:18:32,674
As bad as that?

224
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:35,204
Oh, hello.

225
00:18:36,615 --> 00:18:38,741
Well? How bad is it?

226
00:18:38,817 --> 00:18:40,340
You haven't read it?

227
00:18:40,586 --> 00:18:41,779
Not all of it.

228
00:18:41,953 --> 00:18:45,048
- Well, let's just say it needs some work.
- How much work?

229
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:48,218
Well, all the words are there.
They're just in the wrong order.

230
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:52,752
Come on. You look like you need a break.

231
00:18:56,567 --> 00:18:58,057
You were my idea.

232
00:18:58,836 --> 00:19:00,167
I was?

233
00:19:00,506 --> 00:19:02,633
You wrote Christy Costello's memoirs,
didn't you?

234
00:19:02,807 --> 00:19:04,332
You read those?

235
00:19:04,509 --> 00:19:07,843
We stayed at his house in Mustique,
last winter.

236
00:19:08,247 --> 00:19:09,373
The book was beside the bed.

237
00:19:09,448 --> 00:19:11,211
- I'm embarrassed.
- No, why?

238
00:19:11,282 --> 00:19:14,582
It was brilliant, in a horrible sort of way.

239
00:19:14,952 --> 00:19:19,753
How you turned his ramblings
into something vaguely coherent.

240
00:19:20,459 --> 00:19:24,623
I said to Adam, "Here's the guy
to write your book, not Mike."

241
00:19:26,798 --> 00:19:29,732
God, I miss home.

242
00:19:34,506 --> 00:19:37,702
It's like being married
to Napoleon on St. Helena.

243
00:19:37,976 --> 00:19:40,808
- Why don't you go back to London?
- I don't feel I can leave him alone.

244
00:19:40,878 --> 00:19:43,313
There's something not quite right
with him at the moment.

245
00:19:44,715 --> 00:19:47,980
Amelia told me he was very upset
at the death of Michael McAra.

246
00:19:48,052 --> 00:19:49,384
Oh, she did, did she?

247
00:19:49,855 --> 00:19:54,223
Quite when Mrs. Bly became the expert
on my husband's emotions, I'm not sure.

248
00:19:58,029 --> 00:20:00,191
Losing Mike was a blow, of course,

249
00:20:01,465 --> 00:20:02,990
but it's not just that.

250
00:20:03,167 --> 00:20:08,070
It's having to relive everything,
year by year, for this bloody book.

251
00:20:11,210 --> 00:20:12,507
Oh, dear.

252
00:20:13,878 --> 00:20:16,814
You must be wondering
what you've let yourself in for.

253
00:20:19,050 --> 00:20:21,986
Fine, fine. I'll tell him.

254
00:20:22,054 --> 00:20:23,645
They're just about to land.

255
00:20:23,821 --> 00:20:24,846
On Thursday, he's in Chicago.

256
00:20:24,923 --> 00:20:27,084
Actually, I think I'll go and meet him.

257
00:20:27,425 --> 00:20:30,326
Amelia can stay here
and polish her nails or something.

258
00:20:30,494 --> 00:20:32,486
Why don't you come, say hello?

259
00:20:32,663 --> 00:20:36,691
Fine. I'll travel in the backup car.
I can do my nails in there.

260
00:21:25,317 --> 00:21:26,545
Hi, darling.

261
00:21:26,617 --> 00:21:28,551
- How was New York?
- Short and sweet.

262
00:21:28,619 --> 00:21:30,747
Hi, Barry. Hi, Amelia.

263
00:21:31,890 --> 00:21:33,686
Hello. Who are you?

264
00:21:33,759 --> 00:21:34,919
I'm your ghost.

265
00:21:35,826 --> 00:21:36,851
Right.

266
00:21:36,927 --> 00:21:39,294
Don't worry. He isn't always such a jerk.

267
00:21:48,906 --> 00:21:51,034
This place really comes alive at night.

268
00:22:20,672 --> 00:22:23,538
You'll be with us for four weeks,
is that right?

269
00:22:23,607 --> 00:22:24,632
I'm afraid so.

270
00:22:24,710 --> 00:22:27,076
And the bill goes directly
to the Rhinehart Corporation?

271
00:22:27,144 --> 00:22:28,134
Good.

272
00:22:28,212 --> 00:22:30,613
That doesn't include the mini-bar.

273
00:23:14,492 --> 00:23:16,722
All right. He's ready for you.

274
00:23:20,832 --> 00:23:22,321
How's your hotel? Quiet?

275
00:23:22,401 --> 00:23:23,492
Monastic.

276
00:23:23,567 --> 00:23:25,798
That's nice. No distractions.

277
00:23:33,944 --> 00:23:35,412
Thanks, love.

278
00:23:37,415 --> 00:23:40,213
Hi, man. You ready to start?

279
00:23:40,285 --> 00:23:41,615
Absolutely.

280
00:23:58,170 --> 00:24:00,400
- Is the manuscript loaded on this?
- It is.

281
00:24:00,471 --> 00:24:01,461
Can I have it?

282
00:24:01,539 --> 00:24:03,473
I'm sorry,
that would be a security risk.

283
00:24:04,375 --> 00:24:06,207
You mean I've got to retype
the whole manuscript?

284
00:24:06,278 --> 00:24:08,644
Have you really got my entire book
on that little thing?

285
00:24:08,712 --> 00:24:10,374
We can get 100 books on it, Adam.

286
00:24:10,449 --> 00:24:13,645
And it can be copied in a flash.
That's the trouble.

287
00:24:13,718 --> 00:24:14,945
Amazing.

288
00:24:15,787 --> 00:24:18,414
You know the worst thing about my life?
You get so out of touch.

289
00:24:18,490 --> 00:24:21,721
Everything's done for you.
You don't drive, you don't carry money.

290
00:24:21,792 --> 00:24:25,092
If I need cash,
I have to borrow it from the protection boys.

291
00:24:25,896 --> 00:24:28,092
This is the kind of details
we need in the memoirs.

292
00:24:28,165 --> 00:24:31,328
I couldn't put that in.
People would think I was a complete idiot.

293
00:24:31,403 --> 00:24:35,669
No, not at all. No, this shows what it's like
being Prime Minister.

294
00:24:35,740 --> 00:24:37,537
That's exactly
what the readers want to know.

295
00:24:37,608 --> 00:24:41,170
How does it feel to run a country?
How does it feel to be so cut off?

296
00:24:41,246 --> 00:24:43,270
How does it feel to be so hated?

297
00:24:43,347 --> 00:24:44,679
Thanks a lot.

298
00:24:44,749 --> 00:24:46,511
And so loved.

299
00:24:46,585 --> 00:24:48,143
Amelia, what do you think?

300
00:24:48,220 --> 00:24:50,779
I think I should leave you two alone.

301
00:24:59,498 --> 00:25:02,228
So, how do we go about this?

302
00:25:03,335 --> 00:25:04,926
I interview you.

303
00:25:05,804 --> 00:25:07,738
I turn your answers into prose.

304
00:25:07,806 --> 00:25:10,775
Here and there, I'll add linking passages,
imitating your voice.

305
00:25:10,842 --> 00:25:11,933
Okay.

306
00:25:13,377 --> 00:25:16,006
- You heard about Mike?
- Yes. I'm sorry.

307
00:25:19,550 --> 00:25:22,179
We should put in
something nice about him.

308
00:25:22,253 --> 00:25:24,188
I think his mother would like that.

309
00:25:24,256 --> 00:25:25,621
Of course.

310
00:25:29,059 --> 00:25:32,722
Well, um, the first thing that struck me was,

311
00:25:32,998 --> 00:25:34,795
you became such a successful politician

312
00:25:34,865 --> 00:25:37,460
precisely because
you didn't appear to be a politician.

313
00:25:37,536 --> 00:25:40,163
It's certainly not something I wanted to do
when I was younger.

314
00:25:40,238 --> 00:25:42,865
I thought most student politicians
were complete nerds.

315
00:25:42,941 --> 00:25:46,205
Well, I'm with you there.
So, what turned you on to politics?

316
00:25:47,711 --> 00:25:49,509
Turned me on, indeed.

317
00:25:51,682 --> 00:25:56,847
Let's see, I was 23, something like that,
a couple of years out of Cambridge.

318
00:25:57,888 --> 00:26:01,518
And I remember it was a Sunday afternoon,
it was raining.

319
00:26:01,593 --> 00:26:05,289
I was still in bed.
And someone starts knocking at the door.

320
00:26:06,565 --> 00:26:09,227
And, you know,
I'd been out the night before

321
00:26:09,300 --> 00:26:11,826
and had a few drinks and what have you.

322
00:26:11,903 --> 00:26:14,701
So, I get the pillow and I put it
over my head, and it starts up again.

323
00:26:14,772 --> 00:26:16,297
Knock, knock, knock, knock!

324
00:26:16,374 --> 00:26:20,333
And I get up, I'm swearing,
I go to the door and there's this girl.

325
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:24,314
She's soaking wet, but she just launches
into this speech about the local elections.

326
00:26:24,382 --> 00:26:25,905
And that's it.

327
00:26:27,652 --> 00:26:29,915
- I'm in love.
- And this is Ruth?

328
00:26:30,689 --> 00:26:32,316
This is Ruth.

329
00:26:33,525 --> 00:26:36,961
And the only way I can see her again
is to join the party and hand out leaflets.

330
00:26:37,028 --> 00:26:38,494
This is great.

331
00:26:39,463 --> 00:26:40,556
You want to use this?

332
00:26:40,632 --> 00:26:43,362
Use it? I think we should open
the whole book like this.

333
00:26:43,434 --> 00:26:45,299
"I went into politics out of love,

334
00:26:45,369 --> 00:26:49,534
"not love for a party or an ideology,
but out of love for a woman."

335
00:26:51,375 --> 00:26:53,366
Could you transcribe this
as quickly as possible, please?

336
00:26:53,444 --> 00:26:54,776
Of course.

337
00:26:55,313 --> 00:26:56,644
- Thanks.
- How's it going?

338
00:26:56,714 --> 00:26:58,615
Pretty well. He keeps calling me "man."

339
00:26:58,682 --> 00:27:01,709
He always does that
when he can't remember someone's name.

340
00:27:01,786 --> 00:27:04,084
There are sandwiches in the kitchen.

341
00:29:03,641 --> 00:29:05,199
Oh, shit.

342
00:29:06,711 --> 00:29:08,008
It's awful.

343
00:29:08,078 --> 00:29:10,047
I'm sorry, sir.
I didn't realize there was anyone up there.

344
00:29:10,115 --> 00:29:11,605
What on earth is going on?

345
00:29:11,682 --> 00:29:14,277
It's just a security drill, sir.
We have it once a week.

346
00:29:14,352 --> 00:29:17,048
So, there you are.
I'd rather lost track of you.

347
00:29:17,122 --> 00:29:19,249
I'm a big boy now.
Can't keep your eye on me all the time.

348
00:29:19,324 --> 00:29:21,815
Don't wander around on your own.
The security boys don't like it.

349
00:29:21,893 --> 00:29:23,053
Gotcha.

350
00:29:26,096 --> 00:29:29,430
- Did you win?
- Didn't play tennis. Gym.

351
00:29:31,869 --> 00:29:34,805
Gym? What's he in training for?
The Olympics?

352
00:29:36,406 --> 00:29:38,307
Here's your transcript.

353
00:29:45,884 --> 00:29:47,714
Cambridge. Let's talk about that.

354
00:29:49,253 --> 00:29:50,380
Sorry? Um...

355
00:29:51,088 --> 00:29:52,453
Cambridge?

356
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:57,051
It was such a long time ago,
I can hardly remember.

357
00:29:57,127 --> 00:29:58,685
You did a lot of acting?

358
00:29:59,364 --> 00:30:00,455
Some.

359
00:30:01,365 --> 00:30:04,130
It must have been good training
for politics, acting?

360
00:30:04,701 --> 00:30:06,567
It was a good way to meet girls.

361
00:30:06,637 --> 00:30:09,128
Let's not put that in, by the way, okay?

362
00:30:09,207 --> 00:30:11,903
Still, acting must have been
very important to you.

363
00:30:11,976 --> 00:30:13,340
Okay, let's say I enjoyed it.

364
00:30:13,411 --> 00:30:15,402
You know, you go on the stage,
pretend to be somebody else,

365
00:30:15,480 --> 00:30:18,142
and people actually applaud you for it.

366
00:30:18,215 --> 00:30:19,682
Good, that's more like it. Let's put that in.

367
00:30:19,750 --> 00:30:20,775
- No.
- Why not?

368
00:30:20,852 --> 00:30:22,717
Because these are the memoirs
of a Prime Minister.

369
00:30:22,787 --> 00:30:25,017
And whenever my opponents were stuck
with something to hit me with,

370
00:30:25,088 --> 00:30:27,147
they always said I was a bloody actor!

371
00:30:27,224 --> 00:30:30,557
Do you know what the <i>Times of London</i>
said the day I resigned?

372
00:30:30,627 --> 00:30:32,561
"Kindly leave the stage."

373
00:30:32,630 --> 00:30:36,224
So, no, we won't dwell, if you don't mind,
on my student days as an actor.

374
00:30:36,300 --> 00:30:39,134
We leave it exactly the way Mike wrote it.

375
00:30:41,038 --> 00:30:42,232
Would you like to take
a break for a minute?

376
00:30:42,307 --> 00:30:45,640
Actually, that would be a good idea,
thank you. I need to make a call.

377
00:30:59,590 --> 00:31:01,115
What a bastard.

378
00:31:04,394 --> 00:31:05,862
Look at this.

379
00:31:10,667 --> 00:31:13,192
"Former British Foreign Secretary
Richard Rycart

380
00:31:13,270 --> 00:31:16,330
"has asked the International Criminal Court
in The Hague to investigate allegations

381
00:31:16,406 --> 00:31:18,432
"that the former British Prime Minister
Adam Lang

382
00:31:18,509 --> 00:31:21,103
"ordered the illegal handover
of terrorist suspects

383
00:31:21,712 --> 00:31:23,270
"for torture by the CIA."

384
00:31:24,548 --> 00:31:25,709
Don't!

385
00:31:28,920 --> 00:31:30,478
The pack is on the move.

386
00:31:30,555 --> 00:31:32,385
Unplug all the phones.

387
00:31:32,923 --> 00:31:35,915
Is Ruth still out walking?
Shit! She is, isn't she?

388
00:31:35,993 --> 00:31:38,359
- Barry! Barry!
- Yeah.

389
00:31:38,429 --> 00:31:41,921
Would you please find Mrs. Lang
and get her back here as soon as you can?

390
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:43,626
- Right.
- Let's go.

391
00:31:44,769 --> 00:31:46,430
- Rycart has made a statement.
- Yes, I know.

392
00:31:46,503 --> 00:31:47,835
- He just called me.
- It's unbelievable.

393
00:31:47,905 --> 00:31:50,170
He wanted very much to let me know
it was nothing personal.

394
00:31:50,240 --> 00:31:52,266
He wanted very, very much to tell me
that it was only

395
00:31:52,343 --> 00:31:56,244
because of his well-known stand
on human rights

396
00:31:56,314 --> 00:31:58,612
that he couldn't keep quiet any longer.

397
00:31:58,682 --> 00:32:02,210
"His well-known stand on human rights."
Dear God!

398
00:32:08,558 --> 00:32:11,288
- Sorry to lose my temper earlier.
- Forget it.

399
00:32:12,864 --> 00:32:14,763
And have you told her?

400
00:32:15,266 --> 00:32:17,733
- Yes. Just called her.
- And how did she take it?

401
00:32:17,801 --> 00:32:20,066
Sorry, Adam. This is running on AP.

402
00:32:22,105 --> 00:32:23,868
"According to sources in The Hague,

403
00:32:23,942 --> 00:32:27,105
"the prosecutor's office
of the International Criminal Court

404
00:32:27,178 --> 00:32:29,077
"will issue a statement in the morning."

405
00:32:29,146 --> 00:32:30,443
Oh, Adam.

406
00:32:31,548 --> 00:32:32,913
Thank you, Alice.

407
00:32:32,983 --> 00:32:36,146
Why weren't we given some warning
of this? Where's Downing Street?

408
00:32:36,220 --> 00:32:37,346
The phones are disconnected.

409
00:32:37,422 --> 00:32:38,945
Switch is probably
trying to get through now.

410
00:32:39,022 --> 00:32:43,255
Now? What freaking use is now?
What are you people doing?

411
00:32:43,327 --> 00:32:44,488
I mean, you're not telling me that

412
00:32:44,561 --> 00:32:46,222
the Cabinet Office
didn't know this was coming?

413
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:49,460
The war crimes court doesn't warn
a suspect who's under investigation.

414
00:32:49,534 --> 00:32:51,933
That's what Adam is now, a suspect?

415
00:32:52,002 --> 00:32:53,265
You need to call Sid Kroll.

416
00:32:53,337 --> 00:32:55,363
I think we should call London first.

417
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:58,932
Adam! If it suits them,
they will hang you out to dry.

418
00:32:59,009 --> 00:33:01,136
You need a lawyer. Call Sid.

419
00:33:02,579 --> 00:33:05,413
- Get Sid on the line.
- What about the media?

420
00:33:05,482 --> 00:33:07,951
Issue a holding statement, something short.

421
00:33:08,019 --> 00:33:09,816
This is when we need Mike.

422
00:33:09,886 --> 00:33:11,650
I'll write something.

423
00:33:11,722 --> 00:33:14,088
Let him do it.
He's supposed to be the writer.

424
00:33:14,157 --> 00:33:16,455
- Hang on a minute.
- I should sound confident.

425
00:33:16,527 --> 00:33:19,962
Not defensive, that'd be fatal.
But I shouldn't be cocky.

426
00:33:20,030 --> 00:33:21,726
No bitterness, no anger, and don't say

427
00:33:21,798 --> 00:33:25,234
I'm pleased at this opportunity
to clear my name or any balls like that.

428
00:33:25,303 --> 00:33:27,634
So, you're not defensive,
but you're not cocky.

429
00:33:27,704 --> 00:33:29,297
You're not angry, but you're not pleased?

430
00:33:29,374 --> 00:33:31,968
- That's it.
- Then what exactly are you?

431
00:33:35,113 --> 00:33:36,340
Told you he was funny.

432
00:33:36,413 --> 00:33:39,247
I've always been a passionate supporter...

433
00:33:39,317 --> 00:33:40,807
No, scrub that.

434
00:33:41,419 --> 00:33:44,650
I've always been
a strong, no, committed supporter

435
00:33:44,721 --> 00:33:48,157
of the work
of the International Criminal Court. Has he?

436
00:33:48,558 --> 00:33:49,855
You're the writer.

437
00:33:49,926 --> 00:33:52,520
The struggle against terror is too important

438
00:33:52,596 --> 00:33:55,724
to be used for the purposes
of personal revenge.

439
00:33:56,433 --> 00:33:59,732
Very good.
You could be the new Mike McAra.

440
00:34:01,538 --> 00:34:03,439
- Hello?
- <i>John Maddox.</i>

441
00:34:03,508 --> 00:34:07,273
<i>This is gonna be big.</i>
<i>This can only be good for us.</i>

442
00:34:07,345 --> 00:34:10,041
- Could be.
<i>- Here's the first chapter right here.</i>

443
00:34:10,114 --> 00:34:11,342
Okay.

444
00:34:11,416 --> 00:34:13,509
<i>What've you covered so far?</i>

445
00:34:13,684 --> 00:34:14,809
Um...

446
00:34:15,452 --> 00:34:17,784
The early years, childhood, university.

447
00:34:17,855 --> 00:34:20,688
<i>All right, forget that crap.</i>
<i>Get him focused on the war crimes.</i>

448
00:34:20,757 --> 00:34:23,521
<i>And he can't talk to anybody else, all right?</i>

449
00:34:23,594 --> 00:34:25,425
- Right.
<i>- It's gotta be our exclusive.</i>

450
00:34:25,496 --> 00:34:27,157
<i>Any chance of you</i>
<i>finishing the manuscript sooner?</i>

451
00:34:27,231 --> 00:34:28,219
Sooner?

452
00:34:28,298 --> 00:34:30,027
<i>Yeah, yeah, sooner.</i>

453
00:34:30,701 --> 00:34:32,134
Well, how much sooner?

454
00:34:32,202 --> 00:34:34,068
<i>I'm thinking two weeks.</i>

455
00:34:35,440 --> 00:34:36,634
Jesus.

456
00:34:37,407 --> 00:34:40,001
<i>Look, I know it's tough,</i>
<i>but if anyone can do it, you can.</i>

457
00:34:40,077 --> 00:34:42,409
<i>I'm relying on you. We'll talk.</i>

458
00:34:49,853 --> 00:34:50,911
Shit.

459
00:34:56,293 --> 00:34:57,590
I'd never have guessed you smoked.

460
00:34:57,661 --> 00:35:01,358
I only allow myself one
at times of great stress or contentment.

461
00:35:01,431 --> 00:35:03,865
- And which is this?
- Very funny.

462
00:35:03,934 --> 00:35:06,266
Maddox just called. He wants the book
in two weeks instead of four.

463
00:35:06,336 --> 00:35:07,565
Christ. Good luck.

464
00:35:07,637 --> 00:35:11,164
Yeah, I wouldn't mind a lift back to my
hotel. I could get on with some work there.

465
00:35:11,242 --> 00:35:12,708
You're not planning on
taking that manuscript

466
00:35:12,777 --> 00:35:14,641
- out of here, are you?
- Course not.

467
00:35:14,711 --> 00:35:17,579
Because you do realize
how serious this is getting, don't you?

468
00:35:17,648 --> 00:35:20,617
- You can search me, if you like.
- That won't be necessary.

469
00:35:22,286 --> 00:35:25,880
All right. Fetch your stuff.
I'll get one of the boys to take you.

470
00:35:26,590 --> 00:35:29,559
<i>Mr. Lang insisted he had always been</i>
<i>a committed supporter</i>

471
00:35:29,626 --> 00:35:32,596
<i>of the work</i>
<i>of the International Criminal Court.</i>

472
00:35:32,663 --> 00:35:34,255
<i>Mr. Lang added, quote,</i>

473
00:35:34,331 --> 00:35:36,664
<i>"The struggle against terror</i>
<i>is too important</i>

474
00:35:36,733 --> 00:35:39,327
<i>"to be used for the purposes</i>
<i>of personal revenge."</i>

475
00:35:39,402 --> 00:35:41,371
- Same again, sir?
<i>- This is being widely interpreted as...</i>

476
00:35:41,438 --> 00:35:42,871
- Yes, thanks.
<i>...an attack on the former British</i>

477
00:35:42,940 --> 00:35:46,431
<i>Foreign Secretary Richard Rycart,</i>
<i>who has asked...</i>

478
00:35:46,510 --> 00:35:47,670
Could we change the channel?

479
00:35:47,744 --> 00:35:49,735
- Sure.
- Thanks.

480
00:35:49,813 --> 00:35:53,271
<i>At issue is the practice</i>
<i>of so-called waterboarding,</i>

481
00:35:53,351 --> 00:35:55,478
<i>an interrogation technique</i>
<i>considered a war...</i>

482
00:35:57,722 --> 00:36:00,588
- Something to eat?
- What've you got?

483
00:36:00,657 --> 00:36:04,219
- Club sandwich. Clam chowder.
